@jerome-poisson the issue is that mypy complains about reassigning another type to variable `e` right after try/except block (https://github.com/superdesk/superdesk-core/pull/1965/files#diff-4d8b5e2477ab2c27d07c028d86b5cf71R442). It's a generic hint and I think it's useful to have it switched on. Python does not really care about it, but from code style point of view it's better to have this hint on.
What I don't understand in this particular case is why mypy complains about it "here", because variable `e` is only defined in `except` context.
I will explore it and possibly switch it off if possible, the current behavior is weird IMO.

There is a utility function, currently exposed for OpenBSD only, which can convert this kvm error:
https://github.com/giampaolo/psutil/blob/994c429c010049a6a0556ce3b0d1af1f86f27867/psutil/arch/openbsd/specific.c#L50-L61

I think it makes sense to move `convert_kvm_err` out of `psutil/arch/openbsd/specific.c` and put it into `psutil/_psutil_common.c` (guarded by an `#ifdef BSD...`) so that you can invoke it from this file, like this:

```c
    if (! kd) {
        convert_kvm_err("kvm_openfiles", errbuf);
        return NULL;
    }
```

