This is following the same use of another [part of the code](https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/119df62cbddce9d3e10b0a56d7fbf9d53c7fa218/examples/platforms/simulation/radio.c#L843-L846):
```
void radioTransmit(struct RadioMessage *aMessage, const struct otRadioFrame *aFrame)
{
#if OPENTHREAD_SIMULATION_VIRTUAL_TIME == 0
    ssize_t            rval;
    struct sockaddr_in sockaddr;

    memset(&sockaddr, 0, sizeof(sockaddr));
    sockaddr.sin_family = AF_INET;
    inet_pton(AF_INET, OT_RADIO_GROUP, &sockaddr.sin_addr);

    sockaddr.sin_port = htons((uint16_t)(9000 + sPortOffset));
    rval =
        sendto(sTxFd, (const char *)aMessage, 1 + aFrame->mLength, 0, (struct sockaddr *)&sockaddr, sizeof(sockaddr));

    if (rval < 0)
    {
        perror("sendto(sTxFd)");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }
#else  // OPENTHREAD_SIMULATION_VIRTUAL_TIME == 0
    struct Event event;

    event.mDelay      = 1; // 1us for now
    event.mEvent      = OT_SIM_EVENT_RADIO_RECEIVED;
    event.mDataLength = 1 + aFrame->mLength; // include channel in first byte
    memcpy(event.mData, aMessage, event.mDataLength);

    otSimSendEvent(&event);
#endif // OPENTHREAD_SIMULATION_VIRTUAL_TIME == 0
}
```
I guessed that it could be due to a delay to register the event; hence, the 1us. To avoid problems that I was not aware now, I used the same parameters.

